Default and Custom Match Rules

Identity resolution provides four preconfigured default match rules. Use custom match rules to resolve use cases that aren’t covered by default rules.

Default Match Rules for Accounts

Identity resolution provides two preconfigured default match rules based on Account Name combined with other common data. Default match rules allow you to quickly select one of the four common match rule configurations.

NOTE Identity resolution will match records that have the same Indivudal.Id, even if you don't create a rule to match them.
MATCH RULE NAME	MATCH CRITERIA
Exact Name and Normalized Address	
Business Name (Exact)
Contact Point Address (Exact Normalized)

Exact Name and Normalized Address and Normalized Phone	
Business Name (Exact)
Contact Point Address (Exact Normalized)
Contact Point Phone Formatted E164 Phone Number (Exact Normalized)
Default Match Rules for Individuals

Identity resolution provides four preconfigured default match rules based on Individual First Name and Individual Last Name combined with other common data. Default match rules allow you to quickly select one of the four common match rule configurations.

MATCH RULE NAME	MATCH CRITERIA
Fuzzy Name and Normalized Email	
Individual First Name (Fuzzy - Medium Precision)
Individual Last Name (Exact)
Contact Point Email Email Address (Exact Normalized)

Fuzzy Name and Normalized Phone	
Individual First Name (Fuzzy - Medium Precision)
Individual Last Name (Exact)
Contact Point Phone Formatted E164 Phone Number (Exact Normalized)

Fuzzy Name and Normalized Address	
Individual First Name (Fuzzy - Medium Precision)
Individual Last Name (Exact)
Contact Point Address Address Line 1 (Exact Normalized)
Contact Point Address City (Exact)
Contact Point Address Country (Exact Normalized)

Fuzzy Name and Normalized Phone and Normalized Email	
Individual First Name (Fuzzy - Medium Precision)
Individual Last Name (Exact)
Contact Point Phone Formatted E164 Phone Number (Exact Normalized)
Contact Point Email Email Address (Exact Normalized)
Custom Match Rules

Configure custom match rules to meet use cases that aren't covered by the default match rules, for example, when better matches could be made using Party Identification data or other identifiers such as device. Consider adding some of these criteria to your custom match rule.

When configuring custom match rules, select an object, field, and match method for each criteria. Depending on field type, some match methods aren't available.

To allow a match to be made when a field is empty, select Match on Blank.

WARNING Carefully consider the value of allowing empty fields to match. Selecting this option can result in low match quality or unusably large profiles when applied to the wrong fields or when data quality is low.
EXAMPLE

Matching on Party Identification Number alone works best when you have strong data governance practices in place for your party identifier attribute.

Match on Party Identification Number
OBJECT	FIELD	MATCH METHOD
Party Identification	Identification Number	Exact
EXAMPLE

When you suspect data quality issues with the Identification Number field, adding criteria to also consider the individual’s name increases matching reliability.

Match on Party Identification Number and Individual Name
OBJECT	FIELD	MATCH METHOD
Party Identification	Identification Number	Exact
Individual	First Name	Fuzzy - Medium Precision
Individual	Last Name	Exact
EXAMPLE

Matching based on an exact device lets identity resolution detect matches across profiles created on the same device. The matching algorithm compares Advertiser IDs (Apple’s IDFA or Android’s AAID) to determine a match.

Using the Advertiser Id lets you unify records such as:
Records across apps and Mobile Push
Records created by multiple apps by one customer
Records across apps and offline files, like media logs

To strengthen matching, you can also include the device type and operating system as match criteria.

Match on Device
OBJECT	FIELD	MATCH METHOD
Device	Advertiser Id	Exact

To match on device, map the Advertiser Id field in the Device object. The Device object must be related to a Contact Point App object through a Device field, which in turn is related to the Individual object through the Party field.

Optionally, map the device type and operating system to include in the match rule. When these fields are included in the match rule, records with the same middle name are unified, including null or empty values. Records that have different middle names aren’t unified, including if one of the records has a null or empty middle name.

EXAMPLE

Add additional address fields to make a match rule that’s more restrictive than the default match rules for Account.

Match on an Account's Name and Address Fields
OBJECT	FIELD	MATCH METHOD
Account	Name	Exact
Contact Point Address	Address Line 1	Exact Normalized
Contact Point Address	City	Exact
Contact Point Address	State Province	Exact Normalized
Contact Point Address	Country	Exact Normalized

To differentiate multiple accounts within a single entity, consider using phone number as a tie breaker.

EXAMPLE

Allow for multiple match methods by setting up multiple match rules. This set of five match rules allows for a variety of match options.

Exact Account Name and Normalized Address
Exact Account Name and Normalized Phone Number
Account Identifier -- D-U-N-S Number
Account Identifier -- External MDM Id
Account Identifier -- Demandbase
Fuzzy and Exact Match Methods
Match rule methods determine how source data is transformed for comparison during matching. Changing the match method on a field typically changes the consolidation rate based on that field.
